<br>
I'd like to lead off by thanking you for the polite reply, and while yes, I agree that magicians as a class deal damage very well, VI seems to think that at higher end, we do not need to deal as much damage as before. In most cases, this tends to be accurate, because of the tendancy for raids to be melee heavy. It'd be nice to be able to still deal damage, but with all the major issues with simply PATHING to the mob, a major increase in pet strength would be getting the pet on the mob as quickly as possible insteado f watching it struggle and then poof.<br>
<br>
Wezloc,<br>
<br>
Magicians do deal a significant ammount of damage in pre-50 levels. Magicians are defined by their expansive ability to summon items and creatures. I'm not quite sure how these two statements are either inaccurate or off base. One is (more or less) your statement, one is mine. Let me clarify something, though.<br>
<br>
Magicians do damage through conjuring, be it pet, be it nuke (usually conj), or be it weapon.<br>
<br>
There are two 'timelines' that Magicians currently go through, because of their nature as summoners. Damage output, and utility.<br>
<br>
In early levels, magicians summon great things to deal damage. Their damage output is high, their utility is low.<br>
<br>
As a magician grows in levels, there's a slow falloff. As pets grow along with the magicians, occasionally the pet doesn't gain much power between levels, occasionally it does. <br>
<br>
As a magician grows in levels, the mage slowly accumulates more and more utility items that they become known for. Componentless Levi/EB stones. Weapons, one weapon with a proc (which would actually be used even in upper levels if the ratio didn't suck so bad).<br>
<br>
Over time, a magician's damage output diminishes somewhat, and their utility increases. This is all pre-50.<br>
<br>
After a magician reaches 50, something icky happens. Comparatively to earlier levels, pet damage vs mob goes down steadily, and ever quicker towards higher levels. This is compared to mob damage. Consiquentally, where a mage could solo things with relative ease at earlier levels (blues), at higher levels, even obscenely low blues (just barely dark blue) become quite a bit more difficult.<br>
<br>
In situations where a magician's damage just isn't needed due to risk or a high number of 100% controllable PC characters, a magician trying the task of dealing damage no longer matches up with their former role. More often than not at higher levels, a magician's main damage dealer, the pet, is simply not permitted (in part to environment, in part to social stigma).<br>
<br>
What a magician is then left with is the alternate role of utility, which (with the collection of utility summons) has become marginally usefull.<br>
<br>
I have to point out at this point, that meerly because a Magician summons does NOT mean that those summons are purely offensive.<br>
<br>
The staff summons carry charges of spells on them. YOu know that right? Those staves serve a double purpose. Utility and damage. Gaze, Cancel Magic, See Invisible, and Flare (woo, dat). Frankly, giving a pet a weapon only does one thing. It permits them to hit magical creatures at low levels, as all mage-summoned weapons are magical in nature. The only marginally usefull weapon summon for damage output is the Sword of Runes, and even then, it's limited in it's targets.<br>
<br>
Armor is never, and has never, been about dealing more damage. It may permit damage dealing through increased survivability, but the total benefit gained from armoring a pet is slight at best. Most of the time, it meerly means you don't have to recast the pet, or you don't have to wait as long for the pet to heal. Either the pet was goign to be able to do the damage, or it wasn't. Armor does not improve a pet's ability to deal damage.<br>
<br>
And, while I see this in the argument again, I can't help but wonder why such a simple thing as reading your spell info and understanding it eludes some mages. BY NAME, and BY CLASSIFICATION are seperate.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Damage shields, bolts of fire and lava also shows clearly that the job and function of the mage is to do damage. Conjuration is merely the skill which mages choose to use while doing damage.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Damage shields, bolts of fire and lava are never, and have never been Conjured by magicians. With the possible exception of the creation of fire/lava for a damage shield, damage shields fall under a defensive shielding skill of Abjuration. Bolts of fire and lava fall under Evocation. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Look It Up.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Conjuration plays <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> no</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> part in these spells.<br>
<br>
While the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> possibility</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> remains for these things to have been made conjuration in line with our abilities (except perhaps a damage shield for it's special nature), Verant chose not to do things that way. <p><A HREF="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=52886">Rhasin Firestorm</A><BR>
